The resident in Liechtenstein is studying the COVID-19 virus and trying to model its spread using mathematical equations. He observes that the number of new daily cases in his area grows exponentially, but also that the number of new daily cases is inversely proportional to the total population size (since the virus can't spread if everyone has already had it). He decides to model the number of new daily cases, $y(t)$, as a function of time, $t$, using the following differential equation, where $y(t)$ is the number of new daily cases at time $t$, $k$ is a positive constant, $P$ is the total population size, and $N$ is the initial number of cases:

\begin{align*}
&\frac{dy}{dt}=k\left(1-\frac{y(t)}{P}\right)y(t), \quad y(0)=N
\end{align*}

Solve the differential equation for $y(t)$.
